		  \{M\}=10{\textasciicircum}\{9.0\} M\_\{\{\&sun;\}\}. We
		  confirm that the galaxy stellar mass function is well
		  described by a double-Schechter function given by
		  \{M\}{\textasciicircum}\{*\}=10{\textasciicircum}\{10.64\}
		  M\_\{\{\&sun;\}\}, alpha1 = -0.43, phi
		  1{\textasciicircum}\{*\}=4.18dex{\textasciicircum}\{-1\}
		  Mpc{\textasciicircum}\{-3\}, alpha2 = -1.50 and phi
		  2{\textasciicircum}\{*\}=0.74dex{\textasciicircum}\{-1\}
		  Mpc{\textasciicircum}\{-3\}. The constituent
		  morphological-type stellar mass functions are well sampled
		  above our lower stellar mass limit, excepting the faint
		  little blue spheroid population of galaxies. We find
		  approximately 71\{\}\_\{-4\}{\textasciicircum}\{+3\} per
		  cent of the stellar mass in the local Universe is found
		  within spheroid-dominated galaxies; ellipticals and S0-Sas.
		  The remaining 29\{\}\_\{-3\}{\textasciicircum}\{+4\} per
		  cent falls predominantly within late-type disc-dominated
		  systems, Sab-Scds and Sd-Irrs. Adopting reasonable
		  bulge-to-total ratios implies that approximately half the
		  stellar mass today resides in spheroidal structures, and
		  half in disc structures. Within this local sample, we find
		  approximate stellar mass proportions for E : S0-Sa : Sab-Scd : Sd-Irr of 34 : 37 : 24 : 5.},
  urldate	= {2015-06-16},
  journal	= {Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society},
